title: Vector search basics
text: Vector search represents text as high-dimensional vectors and retrieves by similarity. It works well for paraphrase but can fail on exact IDs or rare tokens.

title: Keyword search and BM25
text: BM25 is a classic term-based ranking function that rewards exact token matches with IDF weighting. It is often strong on identifiers, codes, and rare terms.

title: TF-IDF as a lightweight embedding
text: TF-IDF produces sparse vectors per document. Cosine similarity over TF-IDF can approximate semantic retrieval for small corpora without GPUs.

title: Adaptive retrieval routing
text: A retrieval router chooses among multiple retrievers per query. The router is a decision layer that can learn from evaluation feedback over time.

title: Evaluation loop for retrieval
text: An evaluation loop runs labeled queries, scores retrieval and answers, and writes feedback. That feedback can update router weights or policies.

title: Compounding errors in agentic workflows
text: Agentic systems perform multi-step plans. Early retrieval mistakes propagate into later tool calls and decisions, compounding error and cost.

title: When keyword beats vectors
text: Keyword retrieval often wins when the query includes codes like INC-49217 or user_id=8841. Exact matching can be more reliable than fuzzy similarity.

title: When vectors beat keyword
text: Vector-style similarity can retrieve paraphrases when exact tokens differ. It can work better for natural language questions with shared concepts.

title: Telemetry in RAG systems
text: Logging query, strategy, and scores enables debugging and offline analysis. SQLite is a practical local store for toy experiments.

title: Bandits for routing
text: A multi-armed bandit updates preferences based on observed rewards. For routing, each retriever is an arm and evaluation scores are rewards.

title: Incident reference INC-10010
text: INC-10010 refers to a cache stampede caused by missing request coalescing. The fix is to add singleflight or request de-duplication.

title: Incident reference INC-10011
text: INC-10011 is a queue backlog caused by slow consumers and unbounded retries. The fix is to add backpressure and retry budgets.

title: Incident reference INC-10012
text: INC-10012 is a schema migration rollback due to unsafe ALTER TABLE on a large table. Use expand-and-contract migrations.

title: Incident reference INC-10013
text: INC-10013 is an outage caused by synchronized cron jobs. Stagger schedules and add jitter to reduce thundering herds.

title: Incident reference INC-10014
text: INC-10014 is a partial outage from DNS TTL misconfiguration. Validate TTLs and use gradual rollout for resolver changes.

title: Query planning in SQL
text: SQL query planners choose join orders and indexes. Hints are sometimes used but can lock in suboptimal plans as data changes.

title: Index selectivity
text: High selectivity indexes filter many rows and are more useful. Low selectivity indexes can be slower than sequential scans.

title: Caching layers
text: Caching reduces latency and load. Common patterns include read-through caches, write-through caches, and cache-aside with invalidation.

title: Cache invalidation pitfalls
text: Cache invalidation is hard because writes must update or expire cached data. Use versioned keys or explicit invalidation events.

title: Distributed tracing
text: Tracing correlates requests across services using trace IDs. It helps identify latency hotspots and retry storms in microservices.

title: User identifiers: user_id vs userid
text: In logs and schemas, user_id often appears with an underscore. The token userid is a common variant in tickets and chat, and character-level similarity helps match them.
